"Le Doussal P., Wiese K.J.","Driven particle in a random landscape: Disorder correlator, avalanche distribution, and extreme value statistics of records",2009,"Physical Review E - Statistical, Nonlinear, and Soft Matter Physics","79","5", 051105,"","",,,10.1103/PhysRevE.79.051105,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67650177448&partnerID=40&md5=6c324f36ed459760396c9379a2634cba","CNRS, Laboratoire de Physique Théorique, Ecole Normale Supérieure, 24 rue Lhomond, 75231 Paris Cedex, France","Le Doussal, P., CNRS, Laboratoire de Physique Théorique, Ecole Normale Supérieure, 24 rue Lhomond, 75231 Paris Cedex, France; Wiese, K.J., CNRS, Laboratoire de Physique Théorique, Ecole Normale Supérieure, 24 rue Lhomond, 75231 Paris Cedex, France","We review how the renormalized force correlator Δ (u), the function computed in the functional renormalization-group (RG) field theory, can be measured directly in numerics and experiments on the dynamics of elastic manifolds in the presence of pinning disorder. We show how this function can be computed analytically for a particle dragged through a one-dimensional random-force landscape. The limit of small velocity allows one to access the critical behavior at the depinning transition. For uncorrelated forces one finds three universality classes, corresponding to the three extreme value statistics, Gumbel, Weibull, and Fréchet. For each class we obtain analytically the universal function Δ (u), the corrections to the critical force, and the joint probability distribution of avalanche sizes s and waiting times w. We find P (s) =P (w) for all three cases. All results are checked numerically. For a Brownian force landscape, known as the Alessandro, Beatrice, Bertotti, and Montorsi (ABBM) model, avalanche distributions and Δ (u) can be computed for any velocity. For two-dimensional disorder, we perform large-scale numerical simulations to calculate the renormalized force correlator tensor Δij (u-), and to extract the anisotropic scaling exponents ζx > ζy. We also show how the Middleton theorem is violated. Our results are relevant for the record statistics of random sequences with linear trends, as encountered, e.g., in some models of global warming. We give the joint distribution of the time s between two successive records and their difference in value w. © 2009 The American Physical Society.",,"Avalanche distributions; Brownian forces; Critical behavior; Critical force; Depinning transitions; Elastic manifolds; Extreme value statistics; Field theory; Functional renormalization; Joint distributions; Numerical simulation; Random sequence; Scaling exponent; Universal functions; Universality class; Waiting time; Weibull; Global warming; Probability distributions",,,,,,"Lemerle, S., Ferré, J., Chappert, C., Mathet, V., Giamarchi, T., Le Doussal, P., (1998) Phys. Rev. Lett., 80, p. 849. , 10.1103/PhysRevLett.80.849; Urbach, J.S., Madison, R.C., Markert, J.T., (1995) Phys. Rev. Lett., 75, p. 276. , 10.1103/PhysRevLett.75.276; Blatter, G., Feigel'Man, M.V., Geshkenbein, V.B., Larkin, A.I., Vinokur, V.M., (1994) Rev. Mod. Phys., 66, p. 1125. , 10.1103/RevModPhys.66.1125; Nattermann, T., Scheidl, S., (2000) Adv. Phys., 49, p. 607. , 10.1080/000187300412257; Gruner, G., (1988) Rev. Mod. Phys., 60, p. 1129. , 10.1103/RevModPhys.60.1129; Brazovskii, S., Nattermann, T., (2004) Adv. Phys., 53, p. 177. , 10.1080/00018730410001684197; Moulinet, S., Guthmann, C., Rolley, E., (2002) Eur. Phys. J. A, 8, p. 437; Moulinet, S., Rosso, A., Krauth, W., Rolley, E., (2004) Phys. Rev. e, 69, p. 035103. , 10.1103/PhysRevE.69.035103; Cule, D., Hwa, T., (1998) Phys. Rev. B, 57, p. 8235. , 10.1103/PhysRevB.57.8235; Moretti, P., Miguel, M.C., Zaiser, M., Zapperi, S., (2004) Phys. Rev. B, 69, p. 214103. , 10.1103/PhysRevB.69.214103; Ponson, L., Bonamy, D., Bouchaud, E., (2006) Phys. Rev. Lett., 96, p. 035506. , 10.1103/PhysRevLett.96.035506; Fisher, D.S., (1998) Phys. Rep., 301, p. 113. , 10.1016/S0370-1573(98)00008-8